        "what_missing": "The review does not mention Avg@4/Max@4 over four independent runs.",
        "why_important": "This affects how to interpret reliability, variance, and the very large Success Rate gains.",
        "evidence": "Section 3.2; Table 3."
      },
      {
        "what_missing": "The review does not mention language-specific WideSearch results or case studies.",
        "why_important": "Appendix Table 5 shows English/Chinese splits, and the case studies provide task-level evidence for the decomposition mechanism; both are useful for an experiment-focused review.",
        "evidence": "Table 5; Figures 7-9 / Appendix C."
      }
    ],
    "needs_specificity": [
      {
        "review_text": "Reported benchmark gains on WideSearch are very large and, if reproducible, would represent a meaningful advance.",
        "how_to_fix": "State the exact reported gains and their source: Avg@4 SR 38.50 vs 5.10 second best, Row F1 63.53 vs 38.50, Item F1 80.12 vs 65.70.",
        "evidence": "Table 3; Section 3.5."
      },
      {
        "review_text": "The paper claims evaluation on both wide-search and deep-search benchmarks.",
        "how_to_fix": "Name the benchmarks and protocols: WideSearch with 200 held-out tasks after 20 perturbed training queries, and XBench-DeepSearch with 20 modified training queries and held-out unmodified evaluation.",
        "evidence": "Section 3.1."
      },
      {
        "review_text": "Include strong ablations: without bi-level decomposition, without shared workspace, without memory evolution, without verification, single-agent baseline, fixed decomposition baseline, and different numbers of workers.",
        "how_to_fix": "Separate already-provided ablations from missing ones: the paper already ablates learned orchestrator skills, workboard, worker skill evolution, and exact-backbone single agents; missing or unclear are equal-budget comparisons, verification-only ablations, worker-count sweeps, and statistical uncertainty.",
        "evidence": "Tables 1 and 2; no worker-count sweep or confidence intervals found in text."
      },
      {
        "review_text": "Define all metrics clearly, especially Avg@4 Success Rate, Row F1, and Item F1.",
        "how_to_fix": "Acknowledge that Section 3.2 defines these metrics, then ask for implementation-level scoring details if needed, such as deduplication, row matching, and LLM-judge prompts for semantic cell matching.",
        "evidence": "Section 3.2 defines SR, Row F1, Item F1, Avg@4, Max@4; detailed scorer prompts not_found_in_text."
      },
      {
        "review_text": "The computational cost is not discussed.",
        "how_to_fix": "Make this specific: the paper reports up to 10 workers for WideSearch, 5 for XBench, model choices, tools, and timeouts, but does not report tokens, API calls, wall-clock time, dollar cost, or equalized compute/search budgets.",
        "evidence": "Section 2.4.2 and 3.3; cost/budget numbers not_found_in_text."
      }
